1
00:02:15,674 --> 00:02:17,338
By edict of the Inquisition...

2
00:02:17,402 --> 00:02:20,442
to spread subversive thought
is heresy.

3
00:02:29,850 --> 00:02:31,450
By edict of the Inquisition...

4
00:02:31,514 --> 00:02:34,042
offenders will submit
to purification...

5
00:02:34,106 --> 00:02:36,442
by sword or flame.

6
00:02:41,243 --> 00:02:44,347
By edict of the Holy Office
of the Inquisition...

7
00:02:44,411 --> 00:02:46,299
to read or interpret
the Bible...

8
00:02:46,363 --> 00:02:48,891
is a sole province
of the Church.

9
00:03:18,395 --> 00:03:21,275
You must by no means
prevail with yourself...

10
00:03:21,339 --> 00:03:23,291
that these giants
you speak of...

11
00:03:23,355 --> 00:03:25,851
were ever real men
of this world...

12
00:03:25,915 --> 00:03:29,371
and true substantial
flesh and blood.

13
00:03:29,435 --> 00:03:32,091
Confess!
What you say of all of them...

14
00:03:32,155 --> 00:03:35,355
is fable and fiction,
lies and dreams.

15
00:03:35,419 --> 00:03:36,763
The Holy Bible...

16
00:03:36,827 --> 00:03:40,699
which cannot deviate
an atom from the truth...

17
00:03:40,763 --> 00:03:45,627
tells us of
that huge Philistine Goliath...

18
00:03:45,691 --> 00:03:48,667
who was fourteen and a half
feet high...

19
00:03:48,731 --> 00:03:51,547
which is an prodigious stature.

20
00:03:51,611 --> 00:03:53,915
You blaspheme
by quoting the Holy Bible...

21
00:03:53,979 --> 00:03:55,355
for your purposes.

22
00:03:57,083 --> 00:03:59,259
The interpretation
of holy writ...

23
00:03:59,323 --> 00:04:02,011
is the sacred function
of the Friars.

24
00:04:02,075 --> 00:04:03,995
We cannot all be Friars.

25
00:04:04,059 --> 00:04:06,811
And there are many ways
God leads his children home.

26
00:04:06,875 --> 00:04:10,427
Religion is knight-errantry.

27
00:04:10,491 --> 00:04:11,675
Miguel de Cervantes.

28
00:04:11,739 --> 00:04:15,099
Truth is only revealed...

29
00:04:15,163 --> 00:04:17,339
or dreamt.

30
00:04:27,900 --> 00:04:29,660
Miguel de Cervantes...

31
00:04:29,724 --> 00:04:33,532
in the name of the Holy Office
of the Inquisition...

32
00:04:33,596 --> 00:04:35,292
you are under arrest.

33
00:08:58,782 --> 00:09:01,758
Anything wrong
with the accommodations?

34
00:09:01,822 --> 00:09:02,974
Oh, no, no, no.

35
00:09:03,038 --> 00:09:06,078
They're quite... interesting.

36
00:09:06,142 --> 00:09:08,286
This is what
we've come to regard...

37
00:09:08,350 --> 00:09:10,206
as the common room.

38
00:09:10,270 --> 00:09:12,894
For those who wait.

39
00:09:12,958 --> 00:09:15,102
Do they wait long?

40
00:09:15,166 --> 00:09:17,246
An hour...

41
00:09:17,310 --> 00:09:19,454
a lifetime.

42
00:09:19,518 --> 00:09:21,054
Who knows?

43
00:09:21,118 --> 00:09:24,446
Do they all await
the Inquisitions?

44
00:09:24,510 --> 00:09:27,967
Ah, no, señor.
Not all of them.

45
00:09:28,031 --> 00:09:29,215
Most of these...

46
00:09:29,279 --> 00:09:31,455
are merely
thieves and murderers.

47
00:09:31,519 --> 00:09:32,511
Oh.

48
00:09:32,575 --> 00:09:34,943
If you want anything,
just shout.

49
00:09:36,287 --> 00:09:37,471
If you are able.

50
00:09:39,615 --> 00:09:41,151
What did he mean by that?

51
00:09:41,215 --> 00:09:42,815
He meant to frighten us.

52
00:09:45,375 --> 00:09:47,807
I think they intend us to stay.

53
00:09:47,871 --> 00:09:49,343
You think? God!

54
00:09:49,407 --> 00:09:50,367
Calm yourself.

55
00:09:50,431 --> 00:09:52,607
There's a remedy
for everything but death.

56
00:09:52,671 --> 00:09:54,751
That may be
just the remedy we need.

57
00:09:54,815 --> 00:09:59,551
Good day, gentlemen, ladies.

58
00:09:59,615 --> 00:10:02,655
I regret being thrust upon you
in this manner.

59
00:10:02,719 --> 00:10:06,271
I hope you'll not find
our company objectionable.

60
00:10:06,335 --> 00:10:10,239
I'm no stranger
to similar surroundings.

61
00:10:10,303 --> 00:10:13,055
I've been in prison
more than once.

62
00:10:13,119 --> 00:10:14,239
- Many times.
- Many times.

63
00:10:14,303 --> 00:10:20,639
And often I have thought
the world to be a prison...

64
00:10:20,703 --> 00:10:23,295
a very cruel one...

65
00:10:23,359 --> 00:10:25,471
where all have desires...

66
00:10:25,535 --> 00:10:28,095
few of which are fulfilled.

67
00:10:29,375 --> 00:10:31,679
But how thoughtless of me to...

68
00:11:03,199 --> 00:11:07,135
Enough! Enough!

69
00:11:07,199 --> 00:11:11,328
Noise, trouble, fights.

70
00:11:11,392 --> 00:11:12,704
Kill each other if you must...

71
00:11:12,768 --> 00:11:16,064
but for God's sake,
do it quietly.

72
00:11:17,056 --> 00:11:17,952
Who are you?

73
00:11:18,016 --> 00:11:20,384
Huh? Speak up!

74
00:11:27,488 --> 00:11:29,152
Cervantes.

75
00:11:29,216 --> 00:11:31,680
Don Miguel de Cervantes.

76
00:11:31,744 --> 00:11:34,400
Oh, a gentleman!

77
00:11:37,696 --> 00:11:40,160
Doesn't prevent me
from going to bed hungry.

78
00:11:40,224 --> 00:11:41,920
And that?

79
00:11:43,552 --> 00:11:45,856
My assistant.

80
00:11:45,920 --> 00:11:47,264
May I have the honor?

81
00:11:48,672 --> 00:11:51,968
They call me the Governor.

82
00:11:52,032 --> 00:11:53,536
- What's your game?
- Game?

83
00:11:53,600 --> 00:11:56,480
Your speciality, man.

84
00:11:56,544 --> 00:11:58,752
Cutpurse? Highwayman?

85
00:11:58,816 --> 00:12:01,280
Nothing so rewarding.
I'm a poet.

86
00:12:02,304 --> 00:12:04,416
They're putting people
in prison for that?

87
00:12:04,480 --> 00:12:07,744
No, no, no, not for that.

88
00:12:07,808 --> 00:12:09,408
Too bad.

89
00:12:12,704 --> 00:12:13,920
Might I meet this gentleman?

90
00:12:13,984 --> 00:12:15,872
Your name, sir?

91
00:12:15,936 --> 00:12:17,888
Names have no meaning here.
I'm called the Duke.

92
00:12:17,952 --> 00:12:20,160
And your speciality?

93
00:12:20,224 --> 00:12:21,344
Treason.

94
00:12:21,408 --> 00:12:23,648
I invent false information
about a country...

95
00:12:23,712 --> 00:12:26,016
and sell it to others
stupid enough to believe it.

96
00:12:26,080 --> 00:12:28,896
Seems a sound proposition.
What brought you here?

97
00:12:28,960 --> 00:12:31,136
A lapse of judgment.
I told the truth.

98
00:12:32,224 --> 00:12:34,400
- Did you like your job?
- Quite.

99
00:12:34,464 --> 00:12:35,616
Do you like yourself?

100
00:12:35,680 --> 00:12:39,040
I believe I could learn
to dislike you.

101
00:12:39,104 --> 00:12:42,528
Well, now,
let's get on with the trial.

102
00:12:44,128 --> 00:12:45,472
Trial? What trial?

103
00:12:45,536 --> 00:12:47,200
Yours, of course.

104
00:12:47,264 --> 00:12:48,928
And what have I done?

105
00:12:48,992 --> 00:12:51,200
We'll soon find something.

106
00:12:51,264 --> 00:12:52,417
But we don't understand.

107
00:12:52,481 --> 00:12:54,305
We've only been here
a few hours.

108
00:12:54,369 --> 00:12:56,929
My dear sir, no one enters
or leaves this prison...

109
00:12:56,993 --> 00:12:59,457
without being tried
by his fellow prisoners.

110
00:12:59,521 --> 00:13:00,865
And if I'm found guilty?

111
00:13:00,929 --> 00:13:02,913
- You will be.
- The sentence?

112
00:13:02,977 --> 00:13:05,377
We generally fine a prisoner
all his possessions.

113
00:13:05,441 --> 00:13:06,657
All of them?

114
00:13:06,721 --> 00:13:08,097
It's not practical to take more.

115
00:13:08,161 --> 00:13:10,657
But these things
are my livelihood.

116
00:13:10,721 --> 00:13:12,449
I thought you said
you were a poet.

117
00:13:12,513 --> 00:13:13,729
Of the theater.

118
00:13:13,793 --> 00:13:15,265
Of the theater.

119
00:13:15,329 --> 00:13:16,417
- You see?
- What?

120
00:13:16,481 --> 00:13:17,633
Come here. Come here.

121
00:13:17,697 --> 00:13:20,001
Oh!

122
00:13:20,065 --> 00:13:21,793
False.

123
00:13:21,857 --> 00:13:24,129
Properties and costumes.

124
00:13:24,193 --> 00:13:27,649
You see, I'm a playwright
and an actor.

125
00:13:27,713 --> 00:13:29,057
So these poor things...

126
00:13:29,121 --> 00:13:31,105
couldn't possibly be
of any use to you.

127
00:13:32,417 --> 00:13:33,345
Oh, no, wait!

128
00:13:33,409 --> 00:13:34,785
You'll break it!

129
00:13:34,849 --> 00:13:36,897
Take them! Take them!

130
00:13:36,961 --> 00:13:38,657
Oh, no, Don Miguel!

131
00:13:38,721 --> 00:13:40,673
No. Take them, I say.

132
00:13:42,305 --> 00:13:44,257
Only leave me this.

133
00:13:45,697 --> 00:13:47,777
Heavy. Valuable?

134
00:13:47,841 --> 00:13:49,729
Only to me.

135
00:13:49,793 --> 00:13:51,937
I'll let you ransom it.

136
00:13:52,001 --> 00:13:53,377
I have no money.

137
00:13:53,441 --> 00:13:55,969
How unfortunate.

138
00:13:56,033 --> 00:13:57,217
Paper!

139
00:13:57,281 --> 00:13:58,241
Manuscript.

140
00:13:58,305 --> 00:14:00,225
Still worthless!

141
00:14:01,217 --> 00:14:03,617
No! Wait!

142
00:14:04,673 --> 00:14:05,953
You said a trial!

143
00:14:06,017 --> 00:14:10,401
By your own words,
I demand a trial!

144
00:14:10,465 --> 00:14:13,633
Oh, very well, then.

145
00:14:13,697 --> 00:14:18,657
I hereby declare this court
to be in session.

146
00:14:25,697 --> 00:14:29,473
Now, then,
what are you here for?

147
00:14:30,593 --> 00:14:32,609
We are to appear
before the Inquisition.

148
00:14:34,754 --> 00:14:36,098
Heresy?

149
00:14:36,162 --> 00:14:37,762
No, not exactly.

150
00:14:37,826 --> 00:14:41,250
You see, we were presenting
an entertainment.

151
00:14:41,314 --> 00:14:42,946
An entertainment?

152
00:14:43,010 --> 00:14:45,090
How does an entertainment
get into trouble...

153
00:14:45,154 --> 00:14:46,178
with the Inquisition?

154
00:14:46,242 --> 00:14:48,418
Perhaps they found
an entertainment...

155
00:14:48,482 --> 00:14:49,698
is not always what it seems.

156
00:14:49,762 --> 00:14:51,298
Why are you here?

157
00:14:51,362 --> 00:14:53,730
Somebody has
to stage-manage the stage.

158
00:14:54,978 --> 00:14:57,698
These two have empty holes
in their heads.

159
00:14:58,722 --> 00:14:59,746
Governor, if you don't mind...

160
00:14:59,810 --> 00:15:01,442
I should like
to prosecute this case.

161
00:15:01,506 --> 00:15:02,786
You, sir? Why, sir?

162
00:15:02,850 --> 00:15:03,906
Poets...

163
00:15:03,970 --> 00:15:05,762
spinning nonsense
out of nothing.

164
00:15:05,826 --> 00:15:07,394
Blurring men's eyes to reality.

165
00:15:07,458 --> 00:15:09,314
Exactly!

166
00:15:09,378 --> 00:15:10,946
Reality!

167
00:15:13,634 --> 00:15:17,506
A stone prison crushing
the human spirit.

168
00:15:17,570 --> 00:15:19,650
Poetry demands imagination.

169
00:15:19,714 --> 00:15:23,266
And with imagination,
you may discover a dream.

170
00:15:23,330 --> 00:15:25,890
The trial! On with the trial!

171
00:15:25,954 --> 00:15:27,810
Miguel de Cervantes,
I charge you...

172
00:15:27,874 --> 00:15:31,074
with being an idealist,
a bad poet...

173
00:15:31,138 --> 00:15:32,642
and an honest man.
How plead you?

174
00:15:32,706 --> 00:15:33,826
Guilty.

175
00:15:33,890 --> 00:15:35,394
Bravo!

176
00:15:35,458 --> 00:15:36,578
Your Excellency...

177
00:15:36,642 --> 00:15:38,786
ladies and gentlemen,
my defense.

178
00:15:38,850 --> 00:15:40,482
But you just pleaded guilty.

179
00:15:40,546 --> 00:15:41,762
Had I said innocent,

180
00:15:41,826 --> 00:15:44,546
you would surely
have found me guilty.

181
00:15:44,610 --> 00:15:46,722
Since I've admitted guilt...

182
00:15:46,786 --> 00:15:49,186
the court is obliged
to hear me out.

183
00:15:49,250 --> 00:15:51,298
For what purpose?

184
00:15:51,362 --> 00:15:54,786
The jury may
choose to be lenient.

185
00:15:56,994 --> 00:15:58,466
Clever!

186
00:15:58,530 --> 00:16:00,130
He's trying to gain time.

187
00:16:00,194 --> 00:16:02,850
Do you have a scarcity of time?

188
00:16:02,914 --> 00:16:06,338
Any urgent appointments?

189
00:16:12,674 --> 00:16:16,579
It is true I am guilty
of these charges.

190
00:16:17,571 --> 00:16:19,235
An idealist!

191
00:16:20,931 --> 00:16:25,059
I've never had the courage
to believe in nothing.

192
00:16:25,123 --> 00:16:26,787
A bad poet?

193
00:16:28,451 --> 00:16:30,147
This comes from a painful ear.

194
00:16:30,211 --> 00:16:32,611
Have you finished your defense?

195
00:16:32,675 --> 00:16:35,427
No, no, scarcely begun.

196
00:16:35,491 --> 00:16:37,571
With your permission,
I will continue...

197
00:16:37,635 --> 00:16:39,331
in the manner I know best.

198
00:16:39,395 --> 00:16:40,675
In the form of a charade.

199
00:16:40,739 --> 00:16:41,699
Charade?

200
00:16:41,763 --> 00:16:43,779
An entertainment, if you will.

201
00:16:43,843 --> 00:16:45,699
An entertainment?

202
00:16:45,763 --> 00:16:48,803
At worst,
it may beguile the time.

203
00:16:48,867 --> 00:16:52,067
And since my cast
of characters is large...

204
00:16:52,131 --> 00:16:54,339
I call upon you all
to enter in...

205
00:16:54,403 --> 00:16:57,795
and play whatever role
may suit your fancy.

206
00:16:57,859 --> 00:16:59,075
Governor,
I shall like to protest.

207
00:16:59,139 --> 00:17:00,611
No!

208
00:17:03,779 --> 00:17:06,371
Let's hear him out.

209
00:17:06,435 --> 00:17:08,035
If you've no objection...

210
00:17:08,099 --> 00:17:09,923
and with
your kind permission...

211
00:17:09,987 --> 00:17:11,331
may I set the stage?

212
00:17:11,395 --> 00:17:12,771
Proceed!

213
00:17:16,291 --> 00:17:19,171
I will impersonate a man.

214
00:17:19,235 --> 00:17:23,011
His name... Alonso Quijana.

215
00:17:23,075 --> 00:17:25,571
A country gentleman,
no longer young.

216
00:17:25,635 --> 00:17:28,451
Being retired,
he has much time for books.

217
00:17:28,515 --> 00:17:30,147
He studies them
from morn till night...

218
00:17:30,211 --> 00:17:32,835
and often through the night
till morn again.

219
00:17:32,899 --> 00:17:34,787
And all he reads
oppresses him...

220
00:17:34,851 --> 00:17:35,907
fills him with indignation...

221
00:17:35,971 --> 00:17:38,339
at man's murderous ways
towards man.

222
00:17:38,403 --> 00:17:41,475
He ponders the problem...
how to make better a world...

223
00:17:41,539 --> 00:17:45,731
where evil brings profit
and virtue none at all.

224
00:17:45,795 --> 00:17:47,939
Where fraud,
deceit, and malice...

225
00:17:48,003 --> 00:17:50,499
are mingled
with truth and sincerity.

226
00:17:50,563 --> 00:17:53,635
He broods and broods
and broods and broods...

227
00:17:53,699 --> 00:17:58,692
and broods and finally
his brains dry up.

228
00:17:58,756 --> 00:18:03,172
He lays down the melancholy
burden of sanity...

229
00:18:03,236 --> 00:18:06,788
and conceives the strangest
project ever imagined...

230
00:18:06,852 --> 00:18:10,788
to become a knight-errant,
and sally forth...

231
00:18:10,852 --> 00:18:13,572
to roam the world
in search of adventures...

232
00:18:13,636 --> 00:18:16,580
to right all wrongs,
to mount a crusade...

233
00:18:16,644 --> 00:18:19,396
to raise up the weak
and those in need.

234
00:18:19,460 --> 00:18:22,820
He persuades his neighbor,
one Sancho Panza...

235
00:18:22,884 --> 00:18:24,964
a country laborer
and an honest man...

236
00:18:25,028 --> 00:18:26,756
if the poorer
may be called honest...

237
00:18:26,820 --> 00:18:29,860
and he was poor, indeed,
to become his squire.

238
00:18:29,924 --> 00:18:33,732
He selects an ancient
cart horse called Rosinante...

239
00:18:33,796 --> 00:18:35,108
to become his steed...

240
00:18:35,172 --> 00:18:37,476
and the safeguard
of his master's will.

241
00:18:37,540 --> 00:18:40,740
These preparations made,
he seizes his lance.

242
00:18:40,804 --> 00:18:43,364
No longer will he be
plain Alonso Quijana...

243
00:18:43,428 --> 00:18:44,804
but a dauntless knight...

244
00:18:44,868 --> 00:18:48,868
known as
Don Quixote de La Mancha!

245
00:18:51,844 --> 00:18:52,964
Hear me now

246
00:18:53,028 --> 00:18:56,420
Oh, thou bleak
and unbearable world

247
00:18:56,484 --> 00:19:01,028
Thou art base
and debauched as can be

248
00:19:01,092 --> 00:19:05,700
And the knight with his banners
all bravely unfurled

249
00:19:05,764 --> 00:19:09,988
Now hurls down
his gauntlet to thee

250
00:19:10,052 --> 00:19:12,708
I am I, Don Quixote

251
00:19:12,772 --> 00:19:15,044
The Lord of La Mancha

252
00:19:15,108 --> 00:19:19,716
My destiny calls and I go

253
00:19:19,780 --> 00:19:22,244
And the wild winds of fortune

254
00:19:22,308 --> 00:19:24,996
Will carry me onward

255
00:19:25,060 --> 00:19:29,668
Whithersoever they blow

256
00:19:29,732 --> 00:19:34,372
Whithersoever they blow

257
00:19:34,436 --> 00:19:39,044
Onward to glory I go

258
00:19:39,108 --> 00:19:41,413
I'm Sancho

259
00:19:41,477 --> 00:19:43,749
Yes, I'm Sancho

260
00:19:43,813 --> 00:19:48,549
I'll follow my master
till the end

261
00:19:48,613 --> 00:19:53,445
I'll tell all the world proudly

262
00:19:53,509 --> 00:19:56,165
I'm his squire

263
00:19:56,229 --> 00:19:58,213
I'm his friend

264
00:20:01,509 --> 00:20:03,717
Hear me,
heathens and wizards

265
00:20:03,781 --> 00:20:06,053
And serpents of sin

266
00:20:06,117 --> 00:20:10,693
All your dastardly doings
are past

267
00:20:10,757 --> 00:20:15,397
For a holy endeavor
is now to begin

268
00:20:15,461 --> 00:20:19,813
And virtue shall triumph at last

269
00:20:50,117 --> 00:20:53,349
- I am I, Don Quixote
- I am Sancho

270
00:20:53,413 --> 00:20:55,717
- The Lord of La Mancha
- Yes, I am Sancho

271
00:20:55,781 --> 00:21:00,293
- My destiny calls and I go
- Follow my master till the end

272
00:21:00,357 --> 00:21:03,429
- And the wild winds of fortune
- I'll tell all the world

273
00:21:03,493 --> 00:21:06,661
- Will carry me onward
- Proudly I'm his squire

274
00:21:06,725 --> 00:21:10,437
- Whithersoever they blow
- I'm his friend

275
00:21:10,501 --> 00:21:15,205
Whithersoever they blow

276
00:21:15,269 --> 00:21:22,725
Onward to glory I go

277
00:21:22,789 --> 00:21:26,150
Well, Sancho,
likest thou adventuring?

278
00:21:26,214 --> 00:21:28,934
It's marvelous, Your Grace,
but it is peculiar.

279
00:21:28,998 --> 00:21:30,790
This great road to glory...

280
00:21:30,854 --> 00:21:32,870
Iooks exactly like
the road to El Diboso...

281
00:21:32,934 --> 00:21:34,662
where you can buy
chickens cheap.

282
00:21:34,726 --> 00:21:38,022
'Tis a sign thou art little
acquainted with adventuring.

283
00:21:38,086 --> 00:21:41,030
Only wait, and thou shalt see
amazing sights.

284
00:21:41,094 --> 00:21:42,054
Like what?

285
00:21:42,118 --> 00:21:44,422
There will be
knights and nations...

286
00:21:44,486 --> 00:21:46,118
warlocks and wizards.

287
00:21:46,182 --> 00:21:48,966
A cavalcade
of vast, unending armies.

288
00:21:49,030 --> 00:21:49,990
They sound dangerous.

289
00:21:50,054 --> 00:21:51,398
They are dangerous.

290
00:21:51,462 --> 00:21:54,886
But one there will be
the most dangerous of all.

291
00:21:54,950 --> 00:21:56,742
- Who?
- The Great Enchanter.

292
00:21:56,806 --> 00:22:00,134
- The Great Enchanter?
- Yes. Beware him, Sancho.

293
00:22:00,198 --> 00:22:02,598
His thoughts are cold,
his soul shriveled...

294
00:22:02,662 --> 00:22:04,678
his eyes
are little machines...

295
00:22:04,742 --> 00:22:07,174
and where he walks,
the earth is blighted.

296
00:22:07,238 --> 00:22:10,118
One day, I will meet him
face to face.

297
00:22:10,182 --> 00:22:12,550
Well, I wouldn't get upset,
Your Grace.

298
00:22:12,614 --> 00:22:13,830
As I always say...

299
00:22:13,894 --> 00:22:15,590
have patience
and shuffle the cards.

300
00:22:15,654 --> 00:22:16,838
- Proverb?
- Yes, Your Grace.

301
00:22:16,902 --> 00:22:19,558
Proverb piled on proverb,
you never cease.

302
00:22:19,622 --> 00:22:21,702
No, Your Grace,
I've got a belly full of them.

303
00:22:21,766 --> 00:22:24,166
- As I always say...
- Sweet Jesu!

304
00:22:27,238 --> 00:22:28,710
- Do you see him?
- Who?

305
00:22:28,774 --> 00:22:30,054
The Great Enchanter!

306
00:22:30,118 --> 00:22:32,678
- Dost thou not see?
- What?

307
00:22:32,742 --> 00:22:37,606
The monstrous giant
of infamous repute!

308
00:22:37,670 --> 00:22:39,654
Whom I intend to encounter.

309
00:22:39,718 --> 00:22:41,510
- It's a windmill.
- A giant.

310
00:22:41,574 --> 00:22:43,398
A windmill.

311
00:22:43,462 --> 00:22:45,062
A giant!
Canst thou not see...

312
00:22:45,126 --> 00:22:47,238
the four great arms
a-whirling at his back?

313
00:22:47,302 --> 00:22:49,094
A giant?

314
00:22:49,158 --> 00:22:51,878
Exactly.
How long since we sallied forth?

315
00:22:51,942 --> 00:22:53,030
About two minutes.

316
00:22:53,094 --> 00:22:56,806
So soon will I engage
in brave, unequaled combat.

317
00:22:56,870 --> 00:22:58,790
Hold there, foul monster!

318
00:22:58,854 --> 00:23:00,998
Cease the knocking
of thy craven knees...

319
00:23:01,062 --> 00:23:02,694
and prepare to do battle!

320
00:23:02,758 --> 00:23:04,166
I swear, Your Grace...

321
00:23:04,230 --> 00:23:06,279
by my wife's
little black mustache...

322
00:23:06,343 --> 00:23:08,231
- that is not...
- Charge!

323
00:23:08,295 --> 00:23:10,279
Your Grace, wait!

324
00:23:40,327 --> 00:23:41,831
Surrender!

325
00:23:43,463 --> 00:23:46,343
Vile coward!

326
00:23:46,407 --> 00:23:48,103
Surrender!

327
00:23:48,167 --> 00:23:49,991
Surrender! Have at you!

328
00:23:50,055 --> 00:23:52,135
Surrender, coward!

329
00:23:52,199 --> 00:23:54,823
Vile creature,
do not seek to bleat!

330
00:23:54,887 --> 00:23:56,935
Hold on!

331
00:23:57,959 --> 00:23:59,495
Hold on, Master!

332
00:23:59,559 --> 00:24:01,863
Yield!
I'll show thee no mercy!

333
00:24:01,927 --> 00:24:04,775
- Vile creature!
- Hold on!

334
00:24:04,839 --> 00:24:07,239
Surrender, I tell thee!

335
00:24:07,303 --> 00:24:10,311
Fall to thy knees and beg mercy!

336
00:24:10,375 --> 00:24:14,279
Or I'll rob thee
of thy very life!

337
00:24:14,343 --> 00:24:15,655
Thou art vanquished!

338
00:24:15,719 --> 00:24:18,183
Vanquished!

339
00:24:18,247 --> 00:24:20,455
Vanquished!

340
00:24:20,519 --> 00:24:22,695
- Hold on, Master!
- Surrender!

341
00:24:22,759 --> 00:24:23,399
Have at you!

342
00:24:23,463 --> 00:24:26,791
Surrender, vile creature!

343
00:24:26,855 --> 00:24:28,487
Surrender!

344
00:24:31,623 --> 00:24:33,255
Your Grace!

345
00:24:33,319 --> 00:24:35,303
Your Grace!

346
00:24:37,479 --> 00:24:39,111
Master!

347
00:24:39,175 --> 00:24:40,871
Didn't I tell you?

348
00:24:40,935 --> 00:24:44,071
Didn't I say,
"Your Grace, it's a windmill"?

349
00:24:44,135 --> 00:24:46,119
The work of mine enemy!

350
00:24:46,183 --> 00:24:47,463
The Enchanter?

351
00:24:47,527 --> 00:24:51,816
He transformed the giant
into a windmill...

352
00:24:51,880 --> 00:24:55,080
to prevent me
the honor of victory.

353
00:24:55,144 --> 00:24:57,032
You'd be wise to avoid him,
Your Grace.

354
00:24:57,096 --> 00:24:59,304
One of these days,
he'll get you killed.

355
00:24:59,368 --> 00:25:02,536
Hell has not seen
nor Heaven created...

356
00:25:02,600 --> 00:25:05,832
the one who can prevail
against me.

357
00:25:05,896 --> 00:25:07,560
He's doing very well.

358
00:25:07,624 --> 00:25:09,960
Come, Your Grace.

359
00:25:10,024 --> 00:25:12,520
We'll find a place
to get you repaired.

360
00:25:12,584 --> 00:25:15,144
A knight must not
complain of his wounds...

361
00:25:15,208 --> 00:25:17,768
though his bowels
be dropping out.

362
00:25:17,832 --> 00:25:21,896
But we could find the hall
of some great lord.

363
00:25:21,960 --> 00:25:23,784
Listen!

364
00:25:23,848 --> 00:25:25,288
What?

365
00:25:25,352 --> 00:25:28,872
A trumpet heralding my approach.

366
00:25:28,936 --> 00:25:31,656
There! The very place.

367
00:25:31,720 --> 00:25:33,160
- Where?
- The castle.

368
00:25:33,224 --> 00:25:35,976
- Castle?
- Rockbound amidst the mountains.

369
00:25:36,040 --> 00:25:37,512
- Mountains?
- And the banners.

370
00:25:37,576 --> 00:25:40,520
The brave banners
flaunting the wind.

371
00:25:41,960 --> 00:25:43,368
Blow thy bugle...

372
00:25:43,432 --> 00:25:45,672
that a dwarf may
mount the battlements...

373
00:25:45,736 --> 00:25:48,104
and announce our presence.

374
00:25:51,144 --> 00:25:52,584
But I don't see a castle.

375
00:25:52,648 --> 00:25:53,640
What?

376
00:25:53,704 --> 00:25:55,240
- I do see something.
- What?

377
00:25:55,304 --> 00:25:57,352
- It looks like an inn.
- An inn?

378
00:25:57,416 --> 00:25:59,592
An inn. We will repair...

379
00:25:59,656 --> 00:26:01,448
to the drawbridge
of yonder castle...

380
00:26:01,512 --> 00:26:02,184
and there thy vision
may improve it.

381
00:26:02,184 --> 00:26:03,656
And there thy vision
may improve it.

382
00:26:08,328 --> 00:26:09,448
Reality.

383
00:26:10,568 --> 00:26:11,688
To Sancho, an inn.

384
00:26:11,752 --> 00:26:13,416
To Don Quixote, a castle.

385
00:26:13,480 --> 00:26:15,848
To someone else, whatever.

386
00:26:15,912 --> 00:26:20,008
But for sweet argument's sake,
let us grant Sancho his version.

387
00:26:20,072 --> 00:26:21,416
- An inn.
- An inn!

388
00:26:21,480 --> 00:26:23,656
Governor, a kindly innkeeper.

389
00:26:23,720 --> 00:26:26,568
A brothel keeper, if you like.

390
00:26:26,632 --> 00:26:29,000
And his less kindly wife.

391
00:26:29,064 --> 00:26:31,177
That's right.
A marriage of minds.

392
00:26:31,241 --> 00:26:33,225
- God forbid!
- Mule drivers!

393
00:26:33,289 --> 00:26:37,129
Hard men! Miles and miles
on the road each day.

394
00:26:37,193 --> 00:26:40,585
And a man to lead the men.
Pedro.

395
00:26:40,649 --> 00:26:42,153
- Pedro?
- Pedro.

396
00:26:42,217 --> 00:26:44,201
And for the men...

397
00:26:44,265 --> 00:26:47,689
beautiful women
who please for profit.

398
00:26:49,385 --> 00:26:51,209
Fermina!

399
00:26:51,273 --> 00:26:54,313
And a most particular...

400
00:26:54,377 --> 00:26:57,065
kitchen maid...

401
00:26:57,129 --> 00:26:59,721
called Aldonza.

402
00:26:59,785 --> 00:27:02,761
One to whom life has been
discourteous.

403
00:27:02,825 --> 00:27:07,177
A tigress crouching in the dark.

404
00:27:07,241 --> 00:27:10,953
Still keen in tooth and claw.

405
00:27:12,265 --> 00:27:15,017
- Take it, Aldonza.
- Aldonza!

406
00:27:15,081 --> 00:27:16,521
Come on, Aldonza, take it!

407
00:27:16,585 --> 00:27:18,249
- Aldonza!
- Take it!

408
00:27:26,889 --> 00:27:29,129
Aldonza!

409
00:27:35,881 --> 00:27:38,825
You want this on the table
or over your lousy heads?

410
00:27:40,649 --> 00:27:43,401
There, swine. Feed!

411
00:27:45,065 --> 00:27:46,121
I brought you something.

412
00:27:46,185 --> 00:27:47,945
Keep it till it grows up.

413
00:27:51,753 --> 00:27:53,705
Little dogs have big ideas.

414
00:27:55,049 --> 00:27:56,361
Tonight!

415
00:27:59,177 --> 00:28:00,713
Payment in advance.

416
00:28:02,537 --> 00:28:03,817
Aldonza!

417
00:28:03,881 --> 00:28:05,705
Talk with your money,
not your hands.

418
00:28:05,769 --> 00:28:09,289
How about a nice
thick bed of hay instead?

419
00:28:09,385 --> 00:28:11,113
Good. Eat it.

420
00:28:13,482 --> 00:28:16,298
You refuse Pedro?

421
00:28:16,362 --> 00:28:18,442
Try me. Try me.

422
00:28:18,506 --> 00:28:20,490
My mules are not so stubborn.

423
00:28:21,866 --> 00:28:24,202
Fine. Make love to your mules.

424
00:28:25,290 --> 00:28:27,402
Aldonza, I sell my mules.

425
00:28:27,466 --> 00:28:30,570
Aldonza, I am the best lover!

426
00:28:30,634 --> 00:28:33,802
Who cares? Just pay me!

427
00:28:34,666 --> 00:28:38,858
One pair of arms is like another

428
00:28:38,922 --> 00:28:42,954
I don't know why
or who's to blame

429
00:28:43,018 --> 00:28:47,242
I'll go with you
or with your brother

430
00:28:47,306 --> 00:28:49,962
It's all the same

431
00:28:50,026 --> 00:28:52,810
It's all the same

432
00:28:52,874 --> 00:28:56,970
This I have learned
that when the light's out

433
00:28:57,034 --> 00:29:00,938
No man will burn
with special flame

434
00:29:01,002 --> 00:29:04,650
You'll prove to me
before the night's out

435
00:29:04,714 --> 00:29:07,626
You're all the same

436
00:29:07,690 --> 00:29:09,258
You're all the same

437
00:29:09,322 --> 00:29:10,314
Not me, Aldonza!

438
00:29:10,378 --> 00:29:15,146
So do not talk to me of love

439
00:29:15,210 --> 00:29:18,090
I'm not a fool

440
00:29:18,154 --> 00:29:20,778
With starry eyes

441
00:29:20,842 --> 00:29:26,218
Just put your money in my hand

442
00:29:26,282 --> 00:29:31,626
And you will get what money buys

443
00:29:33,226 --> 00:29:37,450
When I am dead,
no man will miss me

444
00:29:37,514 --> 00:29:41,258
For life's
a cruel and dirty game

445
00:29:41,322 --> 00:29:45,450
So you can curse
or you can kiss me

446
00:29:45,514 --> 00:29:47,114
It's all the same

447
00:29:47,178 --> 00:29:48,266
More wine, Aldonza!

448
00:29:48,330 --> 00:29:50,922
It's all the same

449
00:30:04,075 --> 00:30:09,611
Oh, I have seen too many beds

450
00:30:09,675 --> 00:30:14,923
But I have known too little rest

451
00:30:14,987 --> 00:30:20,491
And I have loved too many men

452
00:30:20,555 --> 00:30:25,835
With hatred burning in my breast

453
00:30:25,899 --> 00:30:27,627
Aldonza!

454
00:30:27,691 --> 00:30:32,139
I do not like you
or your brother

455
00:30:32,203 --> 00:30:35,787
I do not like the life I live

456
00:30:35,851 --> 00:30:38,027
But I am me

457
00:30:38,091 --> 00:30:40,203
I am Aldonza

458
00:30:40,267 --> 00:30:43,723
And what I give, I choose...

459
00:30:43,787 --> 00:30:45,067
Choose!

460
00:31:09,963 --> 00:31:14,827
One pair of arms is like another

461
00:31:14,891 --> 00:31:17,643
It's all the same

462
00:31:17,707 --> 00:31:20,235
It's all the same

463
00:31:21,227 --> 00:31:22,347
Aldonza!

464
00:31:26,091 --> 00:31:28,587
Well, gentlemen,
everything in order?

465
00:31:28,651 --> 00:31:29,867
Did you feed the mules?

466
00:31:29,931 --> 00:31:32,587
- They're eating as well as you.
- Oh, no.

467
00:31:32,651 --> 00:31:34,731
God forbid.

468
00:31:34,795 --> 00:31:37,036
He jokes.

469
00:31:37,100 --> 00:31:39,692
It's well-known
that I set the finest table...

470
00:31:39,756 --> 00:31:41,292
between Madrid and Malaga.

471
00:31:42,284 --> 00:31:44,268
My patrons have always...

472
00:31:46,028 --> 00:31:49,996
It's the pig butcher.
I didn't expect him so early.

473
00:31:50,060 --> 00:31:51,116
What in the name of?

474
00:31:51,180 --> 00:31:54,796
Coming! Coming!
Señor butcher, coming!

475
00:32:03,756 --> 00:32:07,148
Is the lord of the castle
at hand?

476
00:32:08,428 --> 00:32:12,588
I say, is the Castellano here?

477
00:32:12,652 --> 00:32:15,468
I am in charge of this place.

478
00:32:15,532 --> 00:32:19,692
We waited, sire, for a dwarf
to mount the battlements...

479
00:32:19,756 --> 00:32:22,252
and announce us,
but none appeared.

480
00:32:22,316 --> 00:32:25,772
The, uh, the dwarfs,
they're all busy.

481
00:32:30,252 --> 00:32:33,324
My noble lords and ladies...

482
00:32:33,388 --> 00:32:36,044
my master Don Quixote...

483
00:32:37,324 --> 00:32:39,276
- Knight-errant?
- Knight-errant...

484
00:32:39,340 --> 00:32:43,372
defender of the right,
and pursuer of...

485
00:32:43,436 --> 00:32:46,988
of lofty undertakings
requests the...

486
00:32:48,204 --> 00:32:49,356
boon?

487
00:32:50,668 --> 00:32:53,676
The boon of hospitality!

488
00:32:56,204 --> 00:32:58,444
Well, sir, is it granted?

489
00:32:58,508 --> 00:33:00,204
Absolutely!

490
00:33:00,268 --> 00:33:05,452
You see? I mean, this castle
is open to everybody.

491
00:33:09,324 --> 00:33:10,764
Master!

492
00:33:13,356 --> 00:33:14,572
Master!

493
00:33:14,636 --> 00:33:17,100
Master! Master!

494
00:33:21,037 --> 00:33:22,957
Are you hurt?

495
00:33:23,021 --> 00:33:28,077
One of the little mishaps
of my profession.

496
00:33:28,141 --> 00:33:29,293
He's a madman.

497
00:33:29,357 --> 00:33:31,341
Madmen are the children of God.

498
00:33:31,405 --> 00:33:33,389
Sir Knight, you must be hungry.

499
00:33:33,453 --> 00:33:35,149
I am, sir.

500
00:33:35,213 --> 00:33:37,677
There is food aplenty.
And for your squire, too.

501
00:33:37,741 --> 00:33:42,029
Well, as I always say, hunger
is the best gravy in the world.

502
00:33:42,093 --> 00:33:44,141
And as the poor
are always hungry...

503
00:33:44,205 --> 00:33:47,405
they, uh... sir, I thank you.

504
00:33:47,469 --> 00:33:50,861
Stay and rest tonight.
I'll just stable your animal.

505
00:33:50,925 --> 00:33:56,429
See that your grooms care
for my fleet-footed Rosinante.

506
00:33:56,493 --> 00:34:01,133
A horse of courage,
sobriety, and chastity.

507
00:34:01,197 --> 00:34:04,333
A flower and glory
of horse flesh.

508
00:34:05,773 --> 00:34:07,821
Thank you, Master.

509
00:34:07,885 --> 00:34:11,181
- What's this madness?
- Aldonza!

510
00:34:11,245 --> 00:34:12,365
Has he got money to pay?

511
00:34:12,429 --> 00:34:15,021
When did a poor man
ever find time to run mad?

512
00:34:15,085 --> 00:34:16,813
He's got money.
He's a gentleman.

513
00:34:16,877 --> 00:34:19,053
Tell Aldonza
to bring him some wine.

514
00:34:25,165 --> 00:34:28,461
Gentle knights...

515
00:34:28,525 --> 00:34:30,445
fair chatelaine.

516
00:34:33,101 --> 00:34:36,397
If there be any amongst you
that require assistance...

517
00:34:36,461 --> 00:34:37,645
you have but to speak...

518
00:34:37,709 --> 00:34:41,485
and my good right arm
is at your service.

519
00:34:41,549 --> 00:34:45,197
Whether it be
a princess held to ransom...

520
00:34:45,261 --> 00:34:48,397
an army besieged...

521
00:34:48,461 --> 00:34:51,437
the fallen to be raised up...

522
00:34:51,501 --> 00:34:55,245
the suffering, the poor...

523
00:34:57,581 --> 00:35:01,902
Dear God. It is she.

524
00:35:05,422 --> 00:35:08,238
Sweet lady...

525
00:35:08,302 --> 00:35:10,414
fair virgin...

526
00:35:11,982 --> 00:35:16,430
I dare not gaze fully
upon thy countenance...

527
00:35:16,494 --> 00:35:18,638
as I'd be blinded by thy beauty.

528
00:35:18,702 --> 00:35:20,558
I'll get you the wine.

529
00:35:20,622 --> 00:35:23,598
Milady, you must not wait
upon my needs.

530
00:35:23,662 --> 00:35:26,958
I implore you,
speak once your name.

531
00:35:27,022 --> 00:35:29,262
Aldonza.

532
00:35:29,326 --> 00:35:32,686
- Milady jests.
- Aldonza!

